I will take a closer look at each of them.¶

(1)age in "teachers" df¶

Below, I have found that most of the teachers whose age are not shown are Japanese(日本). I assume that this is because most users of DMM Eikaiwa are Japanese and that age is considered to be one of the most sensitive infomation in Japan.

Then, I took a closer look at teachers 12 other teachers and found that they are not due to the failure of scraping. I assume that these teachers were reluctant to show their age for some reasons.

In this process, I noticed 2 things to be modified.¶

  • Values in a "region" column are not correct
    エジプト（Egypt）is classified as "oceania".
    This is my mistake in the process of scraping. This should be modified now.
  • There is a test teacher and this should be removed.
    4017 23161 Standard A Test（テスト）

# Modification of region

r = requests.get("http://eikaiwa.dmm.com/list/")
bs_list = BeautifulSoup(r.text, "lxml")

countries = bs_list.find_all("span", {"class":"text_adjust"})

region_list = ["アジア","ヨーロッパ","北米","中南米","オセアニア","中東","アフリカ"]
region_dict = {}
country_list = []
native_countries = ['アイルランド','イギリス','南アフリカ','アメリカ合衆国','カナダ','オーストラリア','ニュージーランド']

for country in countries:
    country_list.append(country.getText().strip())

for i,country in enumerate(country_list):
    if country == "アジア":
        
        # when asia emerges twice (when the loop is in the 2nd iteration)
        if i > 1:
            break
        asia = i
    elif country == "ヨーロッパ" : euro = i
    elif country == "北米" : n_america = i
    elif country == "中南米" : s_america = i
    elif country == "オセアニア" : oceania = i
    elif country == "中東" : middle = i
    elif country == "アフリカ" : africa = i
    
region_dict["asia"] = country_list[asia+1: euro]
region_dict["europe"] = country_list[euro+1: n_america]
region_dict["north_america"] = country_list[n_america+1: s_america]
region_dict["south_america"] = country_list[s_america+1: oceania]
region_dict["oceania"] = country_list[oceania+1: middle]
region_dict["middle_east"] = country_list[middle+1: africa]
region_dict["africa"] = country_list[africa+1:]



def country_to_region(country):
    for region, c_list in region_dict.items():
        if country in c_list:
            return region
        elif country == "マケドニア共和国":
            return "europe"

teachers["region"] = teachers.country.apply(country_to_region)

(2) evaluation and ratings in "teachers" df¶

These are from reviews of lessons by students, which means that if a teacher has not ever got any lesson review from students (like in the case where the teacher is new), these values can be null. To confirm this, I will visualize a relationship between experience years (1年未満,1年,2年,3年以上) of teachers who has null in evaluation and rating columns.

After doing it, I have found that this hypothesis was almost true, but there are some teachers who have more than 3 experiences, but have no ratings from students. I guess these teachers registered but had almost no lesson so far. I will leave these teachers as they are.

(4)rating in "reviews" df¶

"rating" column in "reviews" dataframe has more than 60k null values. This is caused by the change of the specification of official website of DMM Eikaiwa. I assume that the reviewer were not asked to fill in the ratings of lessons in the past but from some point, they are asked to.

According to the output below, that point is 2016-06-16. It is assumed that rating score system was introduced from that day,

In [17]:
reviews.rating.isnull().sum()

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will explore the univariate exploration of teacher attributes.

  • Distribution of countries teachers are from
  • Distribution of region teachers are from
  • Distribution of age of teachers
  • Distribution of gender of teachers
  • Distribution of number of students who liked that teacher as "favorite"
  • Distribution of each average evaluation score from students for each of teachers
  • Distribution of evaluation score for each lesson.
  • Distribution of experience years of teachers.

(1)Distribution of countries teachers are from¶

The graph below shows that DMM Eikaiwa is mainly supported by Philippine teachers followed by Serbians.

def get_years(row):
    for c in ["1年未満", "1年", "2年", "3年以上"]:
        if row[c]==1:
            if c == "1年未満":
                return "less than a year"
            if c == "1年":
                return "1 to 2 years"
            if c == "2年":
                return "2 to 3 years"
            if c == "3年以上":
                return "more than 3 years"

teachers2["years"] = teachers2.apply(get_years, axis=1)

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will explore the bivariate exploration of teacher attributes.

(Dead End) Q. Are the teachers who teach more lessons more evaluated than those who teach less lessons?¶

The most important and only variables which represents the students evaluation to the lessons is "review score" and "fav count". I will use "fav count" to measure the ability of teachers since univariate-(6) showed that almost all reviews had 5 point ratings, and it means that it would work only to distinguish "bad" teachers.

The variable to evaluate the number of lessons teachers has taught is "n_evalu"("number of all reviews the teacher has got so far"). However, before using this variable as a matrix, I have to confirm the hypothesis below.

Hypo : Whether student posts review or not does not rely on whether the lesson was good or bad.¶

To confirm this hypothesis, I suppose that each teacher delivers same quality of lessons every time. Based on this premise, ......

Since Fav count improves as teacher takes more lessons. So it is not a good matrix to evaluate "good" teachers.¶

def age_level(each_age):
    #for each_age in s:
        list = []
        if each_age < 30:
            return "younger than 30"
        elif each_age < 50:
            return "30 to 50 years old"
        else:
            return "older than 50"

teachers2["age_level"] = teachers.age.apply(age_level)
